<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1864-10-10T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1864-10-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="381" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d381">
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Extract.]</seg></opener>
                        <head><persName type="from">Mr. Pike</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                                Seward</persName></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#left">No. 151.]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">United States Legation,</hi>
                                    <hi rend="italic">The Hague</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1864-10-10"><hi rend="italic">October</hi> 10, 1864.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: * * * * * *</p>
                        <p>There has never been a time since the war began when the current of
                            public opinion in Europe was setting so irresistibly towards the
                            conclusion that the rebellion must succumb as it is doing now.</p>
                        <p>I have the honor to be, with great respect, your most obedient
                            servant,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>JAMES S. PIKE.</signed></closer>
                        <postscript>
                            <p>Hon. <hi rend="smallcaps">William H. Seward,</hi>
                                <hi rend="italic">Secretary of State, Washington, D. C.</hi></p>
                        </postscript>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>